In the second attempt, you place calls to `total()` inside the actual predicates that are used to determine if elements should be included in the filtered list. You actually have no idea when these predicates will be executed: that is an internal implementation detail of `FilteredList`. The predicate should simply return `true` or `false`, depending on whether an element should be included in the list; having side-effects in those methods does not make sense.

You need to recompute the total every time the data change. One way to do this (*which assumes you are not changing the data anywhere else*) is to simply call `total()` in the listener for changes in the search field&#39;s text property:

    private void searchData() {
